02:32:43,655 --> 02:32:46,620
that all that doctor did
was sit and stare at her

2524
02:32:46,655 --> 02:32:49,120
the whole time
she was with him.

2525
02:32:52,120 --> 02:32:55,620
Said if anyone was gonna
tell her she was a loony,

2526
02:32:55,655 --> 02:32:58,720
he better get someone to do
it beside one of the loons.

2527
02:33:00,090 --> 02:33:03,460
Well, you can't argue with
the logic of that, now can you?

2528
02:33:03,495 --> 02:33:04,990
You call that sick?

2529
02:33:21,490 --> 02:33:23,390
Excuse me.

2530
02:33:23,425 --> 02:33:26,420
Could you tell me
if Dr. Quinoness

2531
02:33:26,455 --> 02:33:29,260
still is, uh, living in
Willow Corners, in town?

2532
02:33:29,295 --> 02:33:31,660
You bet.
Straight on into town.

2533
02:33:31,695 --> 02:33:33,090
Corner of 4th and Maple.

2534
02:33:33,125 --> 02:33:35,090
4th and Maple? Thank you.

2535
02:33:35,125 --> 02:33:36,320
Yeah.

2536
02:33:41,260 --> 02:33:44,490
I hope you don't mind
carrying the oatmeal cookies

2537
02:33:44,525 --> 02:33:47,420
but Julia gets pooped
on these stairs now.

2538
02:33:47,455 --> 02:33:49,390
Old places are
built for goats anyway.

2539
02:33:49,425 --> 02:33:52,420
Well, I appreciate your taking
time out to see me, Dr. Quinoness.

2540
02:33:52,455 --> 02:33:54,160
Not taking time out
from much.

2541
02:33:56,060 --> 02:33:58,260
Well, here we be.

2542
02:33:58,790 --> 02:33:59,990
The museum.

2543
02:34:00,025 --> 02:34:02,960
Used to be the only surgery
for 40 miles

2544
02:34:02,995 --> 02:34:05,560
till they built the hospital
out on route 9.

2545
02:34:05,595 --> 02:34:08,220
I use it now mainly because
the sun lasts longer

2546
02:34:08,255 --> 02:34:10,390
than any other room
in the house.

2547
02:34:10,425 --> 02:34:13,820
Lately, I've become
greedy about sunlight.

2548
02:34:13,855 --> 02:34:16,060
Please sit.
Thank you.

2549
02:34:16,095 --> 02:34:19,520
Yes, I seem to
remember hearing

2550
02:34:19,555 --> 02:34:22,320
that Sybil was
in New York City.

2551
02:34:22,355 --> 02:34:26,160
Of course, nowadays, with all the
family either dead or moved away,

2552
02:34:26,195 --> 02:34:28,660
don't keep tabs like I used to. Thank you.

2553
02:34:30,690 --> 02:34:32,520
She, uh,

2554
02:34:32,555 --> 02:34:34,490
has a nervous condition,
has she?

2555
02:34:34,525 --> 02:34:36,590
Mmm-hmm. Yes.

2556
02:34:36,625 --> 02:34:38,460
Ah, little Sybil.

2557
02:34:38,495 --> 02:34:41,090
Little sparrow of a thing.

2558
02:34:41,125 --> 02:34:42,620
Not surprised
it's come to that.

2559
02:34:42,655 --> 02:34:44,520
You know,
she had a nervous mother.

2560
02:34:44,555 --> 02:34:46,420
So I understand.

2561
02:34:46,455 --> 02:34:49,220
Hattie. Pillar of the town.
Did everything.

2562
02:34:49,255 --> 02:34:52,590
Well, I would appreciate it if i
could see Sybil's records, doctor.

2563
02:34:52,625 --> 02:34:54,690
Well, I don't know
what light that would shed.

2564
02:34:54,725 --> 02:34:57,120
You see, l-I never,
never treated her for nerves

2565
02:34:57,155 --> 02:34:59,590
only for the usual
childhood aches and pains.

2566
02:34:59,625 --> 02:35:03,360
I understand, but l-I would
consider it a great courtesy.

2567
02:35:03,395 --> 02:35:05,190
I don't know that
I have anything.

2568
02:35:05,225 --> 02:35:06,360
Let me see.

2569
02:35:08,320 --> 02:35:09,660
Dorsetts.

2570
02:35:10,220 --> 02:35:12,620
Dorsetts. Oh, yes.

2571
02:35:13,820 --> 02:35:16,090
Here we are. Sybil.

2572
02:35:17,720 --> 02:35:19,060
Tonsillectomy.

2573
02:35:19,720 --> 02:35:21,190
I remember that.

2574
02:35:21,225 --> 02:35:23,990
She fought so hard
we could hardly get them out.

2575
02:35:26,890 --> 02:35:28,890
Torn ligaments,
right shoulder.

2576
02:35:28,925 --> 02:35:30,920
Fractured clavicle.

2577
02:35:30,955 --> 02:35:33,320
Palm of right hand
burned on stove.

2578
02:35:33,960 --> 02:35:35,990
Fractured larynx.

2579
02:35:36,025 --> 02:35:37,760
Beans stuck up her nose.

2580
02:35:38,490 --> 02:35:39,860
Gas inhalation.

2581
02:35:42,460 --> 02:35:44,860
Usual childhood
aches and pains, huh?

2582
02:35:46,690 --> 02:35:48,390
Did you ever speculate?

2583
02:35:49,360 --> 02:35:50,620
You know,

2584
02:35:51,390 --> 02:35:53,320
you can live too long, doctor.

2585
02:35:55,160 --> 02:35:56,960
I never told anyone this.

2586
02:35:58,920 --> 02:36:01,490
Sybil came to me
with a bladder complaint.

2587
02:36:01,525 --> 02:36:03,420
Very unusual in
a little girl.

2588
02:36:06,120 --> 02:36:09,690
Couldn't pass her water.
I had to catheterize her.

2589
02:36:09,725 --> 02:36:11,760
If you did a gynecological
on her right now,

2590
02:36:11,795 --> 02:36:14,120
I'd wager you'd see
what I saw.

2591
02:36:14,155 --> 02:36:16,220
Scarification of
the inner wall,

2592
02:36:16,255 --> 02:36:18,890
destruction of
certain tissues.

2593
02:36:18,925 --> 02:36:21,520
I don't believe
she can ever become a mother.

2594
02:36:25,320 --> 02:36:28,820
You know, the good Lord
ships us into this world

2595
02:36:28,855 --> 02:36:31,790
not a whole heck of a lot
better than the U.S. mails.

2596
02:36:33,090 --> 02:36:35,190
But the hand of the Almighty
had nothing to do

2597
02:36:35,225 --> 02:36:37,420
with what I found
inside that child.

2598
02:36:40,920 --> 02:36:43,090
You've been very generous,
doctor.

2599
02:36:47,790 --> 02:36:50,060
You wanna give me
a tip, doctor?

2600
02:36:50,095 --> 02:36:51,360
If I can.

2601
02:36:51,890 --> 02:36:53,190
In your...

2602
02:36:53,225 --> 02:36:55,690
in your trade, you hear
a lot of confessions.

2603
02:36:57,260 --> 02:37:00,220
Dr. Quinoness,
it was a long, long time ago.

2604
02:37:01,220 --> 02:37:03,120
How do I find absolution?

2605
02:41:10,860 --> 02:41:12,590
it happened, sweetie.

2606
02:41:12,625 --> 02:41:14,620
Those are
the crayon scratches you made

2607
02:41:14,655 --> 02:41:16,920
when momma put you
in the wheat bin.

2608
02:41:16,955 --> 02:41:18,790
They were your cry for help.

2609
02:41:18,825 --> 02:41:20,820
Your purple anger.

2610
02:41:24,390 --> 02:41:25,990
It doesn't seem real.

2611
02:41:26,620 --> 02:41:27,820
Well,

2612
02:41:28,820 --> 02:41:30,060
it happened.

2613
02:41:36,760 --> 02:41:39,860
I can't believe you went to
all this trouble after I...

2614
02:41:42,060 --> 02:41:44,020
I didn't mean to
be mean to you.

2615
02:41:44,055 --> 02:41:46,490
Oh, I know that.

2616
02:41:46,525 --> 02:41:48,260
It's just I was afraid.

2617
02:41:49,620 --> 02:41:52,190
Not of what we
talked about so much.

2618
02:41:52,225 --> 02:41:53,690
Can you tell me now?

2619
02:41:53,725 --> 02:41:55,490
I was afraid of the hope.

2620
02:41:57,590 --> 02:41:58,960
The hope?

2621
02:42:00,990 --> 02:42:02,990
The hope that I
might get well.

2622
02:42:07,720 --> 02:42:09,920
You began

2623
02:42:09,955 --> 02:42:12,090
to make me believe
I could, almost.

2624
02:42:15,290 --> 02:42:17,290
For a while,
I could see myself

2625
02:42:18,320 --> 02:42:19,560
painting,

2626
02:42:21,790 --> 02:42:23,760
or playing the piano or...

2627
02:42:28,260 --> 02:42:29,420
yes?

2628
02:42:31,360 --> 02:42:32,820
Being with people.

2629
02:42:40,260 --> 02:42:42,860
Then I realize

2630
02:42:42,895 --> 02:42:45,990
that the only way
that hope can ever be real

2631
02:42:47,720 --> 02:42:49,360
is you.

2632
02:42:49,395 --> 02:42:51,120
And if you're the only hope,

2633
02:42:51,155 --> 02:42:53,220
and this is the only way,

2634
02:42:53,255 --> 02:42:56,560
and if it doesn't work,
then I'm a goner.

2635
02:43:00,290 --> 02:43:01,620
I just...

2636
02:43:03,490 --> 02:43:06,260
I have to be with people,
Dr. Wilbur.

2637
02:43:07,290 --> 02:43:09,160
I know that.

2638
02:43:09,195 --> 02:43:11,860
I've never really
been let in most places.

2639
02:43:13,060 --> 02:43:16,520
Well,
Richard let me in for a while

2640
02:43:16,555 --> 02:43:19,290
and you let me in a little
because you have to.

2641
02:43:20,560 --> 02:43:22,390
But then,

2642
02:43:22,425 --> 02:43:24,360
when he left
and you were gone

2643
02:43:25,960 --> 02:43:27,790
I realized that
there wasn't a house

2644
02:43:27,825 --> 02:43:30,120
in all of New York
that I could go in.

2645
02:43:33,990 --> 02:43:35,320
Quite honestly,

2646
02:43:38,420 --> 02:43:39,620
I...

2647
02:43:41,460 --> 02:43:43,690
I hailed a cab
a couple of times.

2648
02:43:44,960 --> 02:43:47,260
I thought I'd make
up for it somehow.

2649
02:43:47,295 --> 02:43:49,060
I'd eat less or something.

2650
02:43:52,020 --> 02:43:54,520
Because I had to
talk to somebody.

2651
02:43:56,760 --> 02:43:59,460
And one cab driver
talked to me.

2652
02:44:00,160 --> 02:44:02,190
He was very interesting.

2653
02:44:05,190 --> 02:44:07,460
We drove around
for about 15 minutes.

2654
02:44:12,860 --> 02:44:14,020
Yes?

2655
02:44:14,960 --> 02:44:17,490
And he drove me by here.

2656
02:44:17,525 --> 02:44:19,460
And I looked up
in your apartment

2657
02:44:19,495 --> 02:44:21,960
to see if there
was a light on.

2658
02:44:21,995 --> 02:44:23,590
I know that was wrong.

2659
02:44:23,625 --> 02:44:24,760
Why?

2660
02:44:29,920 --> 02:44:33,520
I don't know. It seemed like an
invasion of your privacy somehow.

2661
02:44:34,290 --> 02:44:35,760
With a look?

2662
02:44:37,020 --> 02:44:39,320
I know it's silly.

2663
02:44:39,355 --> 02:44:41,860
No, it only means
there was

2664
02:44:41,895 --> 02:44:43,720
a wish that went along
with the look

2665
02:44:43,755 --> 02:44:45,960
that you think
it was wrong to have.

2666
02:44:45,995 --> 02:44:47,490
Maybe somebody else

2667
02:44:48,320 --> 02:44:50,220
had a wish
just for a second.

2668
02:44:53,460 --> 02:44:56,760
Would you look
the other way, please?

2669
02:44:56,795 --> 02:44:59,090
Sweetie,
it helps me if I can see you.

2670
02:44:59,125 --> 02:45:01,060
Then I'll look the other way.

2671
02:45:11,020 --> 02:45:13,120
It has to do with a dream.

2672
02:45:16,320 --> 02:45:18,260
It has to do with you.

2673
02:45:19,420 --> 02:45:20,760
Mmm-hmm.

2674
02:45:22,320 --> 02:45:25,690
You and this little girl.

2675
02:45:27,960 --> 02:45:30,990
This funny little girl
with a scrunched-up face.

2676
02:45:33,360 --> 02:45:36,090
And she's very young,
so what she feels is...

2677
02:45:37,090 --> 02:45:39,720
well, maybe it's excusable.

2678
02:45:39,755 --> 02:45:41,260
What does she feel?

2679
02:45:43,590 --> 02:45:46,790
She's too young to realize
that you're a doctor,

2680
02:45:47,960 --> 02:45:49,560
not her friend.

2681
02:45:51,320 --> 02:45:52,560
Go on.

2682
02:45:54,820 --> 02:45:56,090
Well

2683
02:45:58,960 --> 02:46:02,090
she wants to sit beside you

2684
02:46:05,760 --> 02:46:07,360
in your big chair.

2685
02:46:08,690 --> 02:46:10,220
And she asks.

2686
02:46:11,190 --> 02:46:12,590
And she does.

2687
02:46:13,790 --> 02:46:16,290
But she's just
a little girl, understand,

2688
02:46:16,325 --> 02:46:17,960
and it's just a dream.

2689
02:46:20,390 --> 02:46:22,260
What worries you about her?

2690
02:46:25,890 --> 02:46:27,620
I'm afraid to tell you.

2691
02:46:29,560 --> 02:46:31,990
That you feel
satisfaction in the dream?

2692
02:46:35,890 --> 02:46:38,590
It's not a dream, Sybil.

2693
02:46:38,625 --> 02:46:40,460
Every time you
come here as Peggy,

2694
02:46:40,495 --> 02:46:42,690
you sit here in
this chair beside me

2695
02:46:43,760 --> 02:46:45,760
and you put my arm
around you,

2696
02:46:45,795 --> 02:46:47,720
and you rest your head
on my shoulder

2697
02:46:47,755 --> 02:46:49,490
and you feel satisfaction.

2698
02:46:51,590 --> 02:46:53,390
Oh, I couldn't.

2699
02:46:53,425 --> 02:46:55,560
I know you couldn't,
but Peggy can.

2700
02:46:59,220 --> 02:47:01,020
And you allow it?

2701
02:47:01,055 --> 02:47:03,820
Of course I allow it.

2702
02:47:03,855 --> 02:47:07,560
Sometimes being close is the
only nourishment that counts.

2703
02:47:10,190 --> 02:47:12,960
It seems like too much
to do for her.

2704
02:47:13,920 --> 02:47:16,120
Well...

2705
02:47:16,155 --> 02:47:20,420
don't you think I might be
doing it for myself also?

2706
02:47:22,020 --> 02:47:24,520
Don't you think, uh,
I might do it

2707
02:47:24,555 --> 02:47:27,020
because I enjoy
being allowed

2708
02:47:27,055 --> 02:47:29,320
to express
my affection for you?

2709
02:47:34,290 --> 02:47:35,490
You mean for her.

2710
02:47:35,525 --> 02:47:37,590
No, for you.

2711
02:47:37,625 --> 02:47:40,820
For Sybil,
for the totality of you.

2712
02:47:42,360 --> 02:47:43,920
Don't you know that?

2713
02:47:47,090 --> 02:47:50,560
I love your courage.
I love your humor.

2714
02:47:50,595 --> 02:47:52,420
I love your talent.

2715
02:47:52,455 --> 02:47:54,760
I love your tenderness
with other people.

2716
02:47:54,795 --> 02:47:56,120
I love your quickness.

2717
02:47:56,155 --> 02:47:58,890
I love your company.
I love you.

2718
02:48:03,190 --> 02:48:05,990
Now the only thing that's
holding you on that chair

2719
02:48:06,025 --> 02:48:08,020
is the law of gravity.

2720
02:48:25,120 --> 02:48:28,360
Sybil, do you know what those
wet things are on your face?

2721
02:48:29,190 --> 02:48:30,290
Oh.

2722
02:48:30,325 --> 02:48:31,960
Those are
Sybil's first tears.

2723
02:48:33,495 --> 02:48:36,920
The first ones you've had
since grandma died.

2724
02:48:36,955 --> 02:48:38,660
I loved my grandmother.

2725
02:48:39,390 --> 02:48:40,760
I know you did.

2726
02:48:42,120 --> 02:48:43,820
I love you, too.

2727
02:48:47,220 --> 02:48:49,790
Would you like me to
tell you a true story?

2728
02:48:51,890 --> 02:48:53,820
Well,

2729
02:48:53,855 --> 02:48:57,120
once, a long time ago, when i
was a little girl in Montana,

2730
02:48:58,160 --> 02:49:01,690
I was lying out on
the grass one day

2731
02:49:01,725 --> 02:49:04,660
just looking at the ants.

2732
02:49:06,795 --> 02:49:11,320
And the grass was sweet
and deep and soft,

2733
02:49:11,355 --> 02:49:13,490
and the sun was
warm on my back,

2734
02:49:13,525 --> 02:49:16,720
and the insects were
buzzing and it was...

2735
02:49:16,755 --> 02:49:18,660
everything was drowsy.

2736
02:49:19,620 --> 02:49:21,620
And all of a sudden,

2737
02:49:21,655 --> 02:49:23,920
I saw one ant

2738
02:49:23,955 --> 02:49:28,390
who was struggling to pick up
this grain of sand

2739
02:49:28,425 --> 02:49:31,920
that was far too heavy
for it to lift.

2740
02:49:31,955 --> 02:49:35,120
And he struggled
and he struggled.

2741
02:49:35,155 --> 02:49:38,220
And pretty soon,
another ant came by

2742
02:49:39,290 --> 02:49:42,020
and together, the 2 of them

2743
02:49:42,055 --> 02:49:45,460
lifted the grain of sand
and started to carry it away.

2744
02:49:46,460 --> 02:49:48,790
Well, I got so excited

2745
02:49:48,825 --> 02:49:51,820
that I hollered to my momma,
and she ran out

2746
02:49:51,855 --> 02:49:55,460
and she flopped down in the
grass beside me and she said

2747
02:49:55,495 --> 02:49:58,090
"now, isn't that miraculous

2748
02:49:58,125 --> 02:50:01,420
"how much 2 creatures
can accomplish together

2749
02:50:02,760 --> 02:50:04,860
when they care
about each other."

2750
02:50:05,960 --> 02:50:07,660
And your mother
was beside you?

2751
02:50:07,695 --> 02:50:09,760
Mmm-hmm. In the grass.

2752
02:50:09,795 --> 02:50:11,060
Watching ants?

2753
02:50:11,095 --> 02:50:12,520
On a summer's day.

2754
02:50:14,360 --> 02:50:15,890
Helping each other.

2755
02:50:28,290 --> 02:50:29,890
It's too green.

2756
02:50:29,925 --> 02:50:32,120
Why did God have to make
everything green?

2757
02:50:32,155 --> 02:50:33,920
Green trees, green grass.

2758
02:50:33,955 --> 02:50:35,760
Green kitchens.

2759
02:50:35,795 --> 02:50:38,020
I'm not even gonna
look at the green.

2760
02:50:38,055 --> 02:50:40,260
I'm just gonna
look at the blossoms.

2761
02:50:40,295 --> 02:50:41,520
Sweetie, I know

2762
02:50:41,555 --> 02:50:43,520
this is the most
difficult hurdle of all,

2763
02:50:43,555 --> 02:50:47,520
but we've gotta get into that kitchen
now and face what went on there.

2764
02:50:47,555 --> 02:50:49,520
I'm too scared of that.

2765
02:50:49,555 --> 02:50:51,520
You're just scared
of being scared.

2766
02:50:51,555 --> 02:50:53,160
You survived it
when it happened,

2767
02:50:53,195 --> 02:50:54,990
and you'll survive
remembering it.

2768
02:50:55,025 --> 02:50:56,490
You know how much
relief you felt

2769
02:50:56,525 --> 02:50:57,820
when we faced
the other things,

2770
02:50:57,855 --> 02:51:01,020
the hands, the-the people,
and Christmas?

2771
02:51:01,055 --> 02:51:03,520
So we will face this,
too, finally,

2772
02:51:03,555 --> 02:51:05,920
and-and-and
leave it behind forever.

2773
02:51:05,955 --> 02:51:08,460
Leave all that pain behind.

2774
02:51:08,495 --> 02:51:11,090
And we'll find a nice
quiet place for a picnic,

2775
02:51:11,125 --> 02:51:12,990
and we've got all
your painting things,

2776
02:51:13,025 --> 02:51:15,420
and we're just
gonna let it happen, ok?

